ce:section.ce:para:
The MTT bioassay was performed to evaluate the cytotoxicity of the CQDs. The groups treated with CQDs/pDNA complexes (at weight ratios of 10:1, 20:1, 40:1, 60:1 and 80:1) showed no distinct toxicity in comparison with the blank group, but there was a slight decrease in cell viability when the ratio was increased to 80:1. This result implied that the CQDs had dose-dependent toxicities. Conversely, the other control groups including branched PEI (25KDa) and semiconductor quantum dots (SQDs) with the same set of vector/pDNA weight ratios, exhibited remarkably lower cell viability (<70%) than the CQDs/pDNA complexes (p
                        <0.05). The cytotoxicity of quantum dots depends on a combination of elements from the particle formulation, such as the core materials and modification ligands [58]. Compared with the eco-friendly CQDs, the semiconductor CdTe QDs may induce mitochondrial-dependent apoptosis of cells [59], with a relatively high cytotoxicity. This result indicated that the developed CQDs possess negligible toxicity and superior safety advantage over the CdTe QDs (see Fig. 6
                        ).

In this study, the transfection efficiency of the CQDs/pDNA complexes was tested in 3T6 cells via enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA). The results demonstrated that the CQDs/pDNA complex group produced a transfection efficiency similar to that of the Lipofectamine2000 (positive control) and significantly higher than that of the other positive controls, including PEI (25KDa) and semiconductor quantum dots (SQDs) (p
                        <0.05, Student’s t-test) (Fig. 7
                        ). This result indicated that the CQDs had remarkably higher transfection efficiency than the conventionally used SQDs, and this is probably the reason why the SQDs have rarely been used for gene delivery. The CQDs also showed compelling benefit over the cationic transfection reagent PEI (25KDa) for gene delivery because of its low toxicity. This high transfection efficiency of the CQDs is most likely explained by the strong condensation effects on macromolecular pDNA, thus preventing pDNA enzymolysis during the transport process (Fig. S2). Moreover, the small size [60] and positive surface charge can also contribute to the high transfection efficiency.

To obtain information about the mechanisms of particle internalization, eight different inhibitors, with three different concentrations for each inhibitor, were used to interfere with the pathways of CQDs internalization. They included NH4Cl, filipin III, colchicine, SOV, glucose, CPZ, DMA, and genistein. As shown in Fig. S3, The colchicine, SOV and DMA showed negligible effect on CQDs internalization, while CPZ, glucose, filipin III, genistein and NH4Cl displayed significant inhibition of cellular uptake of CQDs (Fig. S3). Based on the comprehensive analysis of cytotoxicity and cellular uptake inhibition, the optimal concentration of each inhibitor was established (Table 1
                        ). Fig. 8
                         also demonstrated the fluorescent images of cells treated with the inhibitors at optimal concentrations. Compared with the control group, SOV showed almost no effect on the cellular uptake of the CQDs/pDNA complexes, ruling out the involvement of cytoskeletal motors. Likewise, colchicine and DMA did not exhibit obvious decrease in fluorescence intensity compared with the control group, which indicated that the activities of microtubules and macropinocytosis played a negligible role in the internalization of the CQDs/pDNA complexes. Moreover, it was observed that the CQDs could not enter nucleus.
